,"Ipsilateral cerebellum"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThird order neurones of the spinothalamic tract project from the thalamus to the \u003Cstrong\u003Econtralateral somatosensory cortex\u003C/strong\u003E. The pathway consists of:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFirst order neurones: from peripheral receptors to the spinal cord\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESecond order neurones: cross in the spinal cord and ascend to the \u003Cstrong\u003Econtralateral thalamus\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThird order neurones: project from thalamus to the \u003Cstrong\u003Eipsilateral somatosensory cortex\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Econtralateral cerebellum\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eipsilateral cerebellum\u003C/strong\u003E are not involved in the spinothalamic tract pathway. The cerebellum primarily receives proprioceptive information via other tracts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBecause the tract crosses (decussates) at the level of the spinal cord, sensory information from one side of the body is processed in the opposite side of the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The spinothalamic tract carries pain, temperature and crude touch sensations through first, second and third order neurones.","Third order neurones of the spinothalamic tract project from the thalamus to the primary somatosensory cortex.","The spinothalamic tract crosses (decussates) at the level of the spinal cord, making all higher projections contralateral."],"references":["Dum RP, Levinthal DJ, Strick PL. The spinothalamic system targets motor and sensory areas in the cerebral cortex of monkeys. J Neurosci. 2009 Nov 11;29(45):14223-35. doi: 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.3398-09.2009. PMID: 19906970; PMCID: PMC2796243.","Al-Chalabi M, Reddy V, Gupta S. Neuroanatomy, Spinothalamic Tract. 2023 Aug 14. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29939601.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60261"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16511"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60261"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T23:20:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T23:54:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9202"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74775"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"dat